IP Address: This is the logical unique identifier for a certain network/device on a network. All devices need an IP address to communicate and each consist of 2 parts:
Network and Host. The network part of an IP identifies the actual network it is on (such as a gym or school). The host part defines the specific device on that network.

There are 2 main types of IP Addresses:
-IPv4 (Current but not for much longer)
-IPv6 (New generation of IP addresses)

  -IPv4: A 32-bit string of numbers with 4 sets of octets expressed in dotted decimal notation. This is the old standard for IP addresses as we have literally run out of available 
    IPs on this standard due to poor management and unpredictability of the internet becoming as big as it did. A big issue with the distribution of these IPs was the use of classes. 
    Classes were way too rigid. Depending on the class you were in would determine the amount of IPs along with the what number IPs you'd get.
    Class A: 1-126.x.x.x | 16 Million IPs
    Class B: 128-191.0.x.x | 65 Thousand IPs
    Class C: 192-223.0.0.x | 254 IPs
    Class D: 224-239.0.0.x| Reserved for Multicast Systems
    Class E: 240-255.0.0.x | Reserved for Experiments
    A company with, say, 300 employees would be forced into Class B, would use the 300 IPs that they needed, and the other 65 thousand IPs would go completely to waste. Later,
    engineers realized that too many IPs were being wasted, and there was a growing demand for IP addresses (Which was never thought to be a problem originally considering that
    were around 4 billion available IPs when the internet first began). So they introduced a system known as Classless Inter-Domain Routing (CIDR). CIDR essentially forgets classes 
    and splits a class into exactly how many IPs a company needs by breaking it into blocks like 512 or 1024. In CIDR notation, seeing an IP such as: 129.161.1.0/24, the "/24" 
    represents the number of bits reserved for the Network ID portion of the IP.

    To try and save addresses even further, Public and Private Addresses were introduced. Basically a network would have one known, outward-facing, less secure IP address that would be
    known as the Public IP. No two Public IPs can ever be the same because the internet wouldn't know which device to send data to. The Public IP is what allows a network to connect to 
    the internet. 
    The Private IP is the IP of a device/host WITHIN the network. These are more secure and Private IPs do NOT have to be unique as long as they're in different networks. Private
    IPs can NOT connect you to the internet and NAT (Network Address Translation) must occur so that the router can swap the Private IP for the Public IP, therefore allowing connection
    to the internet.

    In IPv4 the Network Part of an IP address is determined by the Subnet Mask. The subnet mask is essentially a line drawn between what is the Network vs Host Part of an IP is. 
    Subnet Masks are written as such: "255.255.255.0". This is just an example, however in the exmaple, every octet of the IP address that is "255" is a Network portion, while
    anything with a "0" is a host. Sometimes that number isn't 0, and is acually something like 128. Example: 255.255.255.128. In this case, the line for the host is being drawn
    INSIDE the octet, stating that they only need 126 hosts (126 because ending in ".0" would be the Network ID, and ending in ".127" would be the broadcast address. Broadcast address
    is the unique address used to send data to all local devices on the network at the same time. Broadcast address is always going to be the last IP in that sepecific subnet.


  -IPv6: 128-bit hexadecimal string of characters utilizing both letters (A-F) and numbers to make up the IP. Example: 2001:0db8:85a3::8a2e:0370:7334. This is the new generation of 
    IP addresses and is considered to have practically an infinite amount of IPs because it has over 340 undecillion posssible IPs. The sheer number of IPv6 Addresses is enough to
    even possibly render NAT (Network Address Translation) completely useless. Considering NAT was used as a band-aid to make sure that we didn't run out of IPv4 addresses. But since
    for the forseeable future (the next few trillion years) it's essentially impossible to use all those IPs, we would just assign every device a unique IP address.

    IPv6 also got rid of the old Subnet Mask, replacing it with a Prefix Length (Example: /64). /64 are common addresses when it comes to IPv6, spliting the 128-bit number right
    down the middle and showing clearly the Network Prefix and the Interface ID.

    Although IPv6 addresses are lengthy, there are ways to compress the address. As an example, imagine using the IPv6 Address: 2001:0db8:0000:0000:a111:b222:c333:abcd. Rather
    than filling multiple hextets with "0000", what we can do is replace all the 0s with a double colon "::". 2001:0db8::a111:b222:c333:abcd. The caveat is that you can only
    use the double colons one time in an address. If used in two different position the computer can't determine how many 0s are missing from each colons. Although you can only use
    the colon one time, there are other methods for compressing an IPv6 address. For example, one shortcut is removing all leading 0s in a hextet.
    
     Just like IPv4, IPv6 has different types of addresses that serve different purposes. The following are all address types of IPv6:
    -Global Unicast: Is a publicly routable address that essentially functions equally to that of the Public Address in IPv4. 
      Prefix: 2000::/3
    -Unique Local: Is the equivalent to a Private Address in IPv4 addresses in that it's only routable in the Local Area Network (LAN).
      Prefix: FC00::/7 (The "C" in the prefix is can either be a "C" or a "D")
    -Link-Local: Automcatically assigned IPs that are not routable and are designed only to function over a single area of a network. Will never go through a router.
      Prefix: FE80::/10 
    -Multicast: Addresses used to send to computers/devices that are listening for that specific multicast address. Replaced the Broadcast Address of IPv4
      Prefix: FF00::/8
    -Anycast: Shared IP addresses across different servers in different physical locations which allows your network to connect you to whichever server is closest to you.
      Prefix: 2000::/3 (Anycast has no specific IP address so the default would just be the Global Unicast Prefix)


-The Loopback Address (127.0.0.1 / ::1): The internal IP address a computer uses to communicate with itself. In troubleshooting, running a ping 127.0.0.1 confirms that the 
device's own network interface card (NIC) and TCP/IP stack are functioning correctly, even if it is completely disconnected from the wider network.

-APIPA (Automatic Private IP Addressing): The IPv4 equivalent of a Link-Local address. If a computer is configured to get a dynamic IP but fails to reach the DHCP server, it 
automatically assigns itself an address in the 169.254.x.x range. Seeing this IP is an immediate indicator of a DHCP failure or a physical network disconnect.

-Default Gateway: The specific IP address of the local router that a device uses to send data outside of its own local network. If a device has a valid IP but no Default Gateway 
configured, it can talk to other computers in the same building, but it cannot reach the internet.
